Canonical country values are English names of sovereign African countries.

Map common official names, abbreviations, spelling variants, punctuation variants, and diacritic-stripped variants to the usual English sovereign-country name. Examples: `Republic of Kenya` -> `Kenya`; `Cote d Ivoire` -> `Cote d'Ivoire`; `DRC` or `Democratic Republic of the Congo` -> `Democratic Republic of the Congo`; `Congo-Brazzaville` -> `Republic of the Congo`; `South Africa` -> `South Africa`.

Values that are regions, continents, city names, provinces, markets without a sovereign-country name, non-African countries, or diaspora labels do not map to a valid country. Examples that should not map to a sovereign African country include `Africa`, `Sub-Saharan Africa`, `East Africa`, `West Africa`, `Nairobi`, `Lagos`, `Francophone Africa`, and `African diaspora`.
